    <h1>Do immigrant students underperform? PISA 2022 data by country</h1>
    <p class="intro">OECD PISA 2022 data shows a raw score gap of −29 points between immigrant-background and native-born students. After controlling for socioeconomic status, this narrows to −5 points — meaning 83% of the gap is explained by socioeconomic factors.</p>
    <div class="lang-switch"><a href="/faq/pisa-enfants-immigres/">🌐 日本語版</a></div>
  </div>

  <section>
    <h2>OECD average (PISA 2022)</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Indicator</th>
          <th>Score difference (immigrant − native-born)</th>
          <th>Source</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Unadjusted (raw)</td>
          <td>−29 pts</td>
          <td><a href="https://www.oecd.org/pisa" rel="noopener">OECD PISA 2022 Volume I</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>After socioeconomic controls</td>
          <td>−5 pts</td>
          <td>OECD PISA 2022 Volume I</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Share of gap explained by socioeconomic factors</td>
          <td>~83%</td>
          <td>OECD PISA 2022 Volume I</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Countries with the largest adjusted gaps</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Country</th>
          <th>Adjusted score gap</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
